returned by the most southern cape of Africa or America?  I dare notexpect such success, yet I cannot bear to look on the reverse of thepicture.  Continue for the present to write to me by every opportunity:I may receive your letters on some occasions when I need them most tosupport my spirits.  I love you very tenderly.  Remember me withaffection, should you never hear from me again.Your affectionate brother,  Robert WaltonLetter 3July 7th, 17--To Mrs. Saville, EnglandMy dear Sister,I write a few lines in haste to say that I am safe--and well advancedon my voyage.  This letter will reach England by a merchantman now onits homeward voyage from Archangel; more fortunate than I, who may notsee my native land, perhaps, for many years.  I am, however, in goodspirits:  my men are bold and apparently firm of purpose, nor do thefloating sheets of ice that continually pass us, indicating the dangersof the region towards which we are advancing, appear to dismay them. Wehave already reached a very high latitude; but it is the height of